<%- include('partials/header.ejs') %>

<section class="stage-banner">
	<div class="container">
		<div class="stage-header">
			<div>
				<p class="section-label">Stage One</p>
				<h1 class="section-title">Before You See the Family Doctor</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		<p class="section-intro">This is the step most resources skip entirely. Booking a Family Doctor/General 
			Practitioner (GP) appointment can take two weeks or more, so before you even make that call, you should 
			already know what qualifies as infertility, which fertility clinics are accessible from where you live 
			and work, and what to bring up with your doctor.</p>
		<%- include('partials/stage1-steps') %>
	</div>
</section>

<section class="section-light">
	<div class="container">

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>How Ontario Defines Infertility</h4>
			<p>
				Infertility is generally defined as the inability to conceive after 12 months of regular, unprotected 
				intercourse for individuals under 35, or after 6 months for those 35 and older. Age is one of the most
				significant factors in fertility outcomes, which is why timelines are critical.
			</p>
			<p>
				Approximately <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7008682/" target="_blank" 
				title="Source: PubMed Central (PMC)" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" class="green-text">
				one in six couples</a> in Ontario will experience infertility and require assisted reproductive 
				technology (ART) to achieve pregnancy.
			</p>
			<div class="text-center my-3">
				<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/14.png" alt="Illustration of couples" style="width: 100%;">
			</div>
			<p class="mt-2">
				You don't need to wait for a formal diagnosis to start the conversation with your family 
				doctor. If you suspect something may be affecting your ability to conceive, that's reason enough to 
				ask for a referral. Even if you don't have an <span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="OHIP 
				(Ontario Health Insurance Plan) is Ontario's publicly funded health insurance, available to eligible Ontario 
				residents at no cost.">OHIP</span> card, you can still access fertility clinics. Some clinics accept self-referrals, 
				but all costs would be out of pocket.
			</p>

			<div class="row align-items-center mt-4">
				<div class="col-md-8">
					<h5 style="color: var(--navy-dark)">What is an OHIP Card?</h5>
					<p>
						OHIP stands for the Ontario Health Insurance Plan. It is Ontario's publicly funded health 
						insurance program, available to eligible residents at no cost. Your OHIP card is what you 
						present at medical appointments to access covered services, including family doctor visits, 
						specialist consultations, and most diagnostic tests during the fertility process.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted small">
						<a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/apply-ohip-and-get-health-card" target="_blank" class="green-text">
							OHIP eligibility and how to apply 
							<i class="bi bi-arrow-up-right-square"></i>
						</a>
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-4 text-center">
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/healthcard-illustrated.jpg" 
						alt="Sample Ontario health card (OHIP card) showing a cartoon illustration with a sample name and number" 
						style="max-width: 260px; width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
				</div>
			</div>

		</div>

		<div class="highlight-box">
			<div class="row align-items-center">
				<div class="col-md-8">
					<strong>Fertility services are open to all eligible Ontarians.</strong>
					<br>To access government-funded fertility treatments, you must be an Ontario resident with a valid 
					OHIP card. 
					<strong style="color: var(--navy-dark);">Whether you are pursuing parenthood on your own or with a partner, sex, gender, sexual orientation, 
					and family status are not considerations in determining eligibility.</strong>
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-4 text-center">
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/15.png" alt="Illustration of couples" style="max-height: 200px; width: auto;">
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>


		<div class="row g-4">
			<div class="col-md-6 d-flex">
				<div class="highlight-box">
					<strong>Getting started doesn't cost you anything.</strong> 
					<br>Your family doctor visit, the referral, your first consultation with the fertility specialist, 
					and most diagnostic tests (blood work, ultrasound, etc.) are all covered by OHIP. Out-of-pocket costs 
					only begin later if you move into treatments like IUI or IVF.
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="col-md-6 d-flex">
				<div class="highlight-box">
					<strong>Why choosing a fertility clinic early matters:</strong>
					<br>Once you enter the publicly funded stream, waitlists are inevitable. Fertility clinic experiences 
					vary widely, and even your family doctor may not have a specific recommendation. They may simply ask 
					which clinic you'd like to be referred to. If you don't have an answer, you'll need to go home, 
					research on your own, and come back with a preference before the referral can be sent. That back-and-forth 
					costs valuable time. If you already know which clinic you want, your referral can go out the same day.
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>You Have the Right to Choose Your Clinic</h4>
			<p>Most clinic websites focus on marketing rather than educating. They want you to pick <em>their</em> clinic. But the truth 
				is: you have a choice, and your decision should factor in practical realities that will affect your daily life for months.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-2">
				During the investigative cycle, you may need to go back for blood work and ultrasounds multiple times in a single 
				menstrual cycle. Consider:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>How far is the clinic from your home and workplace?</li>
				<li>Can you get there early in the morning for time-sensitive blood work?</li>
				<li>Is there parking, or is it transit-accessible?</li>
				<li>Will the commute be sustainable over weeks or months?</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="info-block clinic-section">
			<h4>Ontario Participating Fertility Clinics by Region</h4>
			<p>
				The following clinics participate in the Ontario Fertility Program (OFP). Services vary by location — 
				<strong>AI/IUI</strong> (artificial/intrauterine insemination), <strong>IVF</strong> (in vitro fertilization), 
				and <strong>FP</strong> (fertility preservation). Click a region to view clinics.
			</p>

			<div class="accordion mt-3" id="clinicList">
				<% clinics.forEach(function(region) { %>
					<div class="accordion-item">
						<h2 class="accordion-header">
							<button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" 
								data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#<%= region.id %>">
								<%= region.region %>
							</button>
						</h2>
						<div id="<%= region.id %>" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#clinicList">
							<div class="accordion-body p-0">
								<div class="table-responsive">
									<table class="table clinic-table mb-0">
										<thead>
											<tr>
												<th>Clinic</th>
												<th>Address</th>
												<th>Services</th>
											</tr>
										</thead>
										<tbody>
											<% region.clinics.forEach(function(c) { %>
												<tr>
													<td>
														<% if (c.url) { %>
															<a href="<%= c.url %>" target="_blank"><%= c.name %></a>
														<% } else { %>
															<%= c.name %>
														<% } %>
														<% if (c.phone) { %>
															<br><small class="clinic-phone"><%= c.phone %></small>
														<% } %>
													</td>
													<td><%= c.address %></td>
													<td><%= c.services %></td>
												</tr>
											<% }); %>
										</tbody>
									</table>
								</div>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>
				<% }); %>
			</div>

			<p class="text-muted small mt-3">Source from 
				<a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/get-fertility-treatments" target="_blank" 
				class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
				title="Source: Ontario Ministry of Health">Ontario Ministry of Health</a>. 
				Wait times vary by clinic. Each clinic manages its own waitlist and prioritizes 
				patients based on the physician's clinical judgment.
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="info-block">
			<h4>Preparing for Your GP Appointment</h4>
			<p>Family doctor appointments are short. Don't go in unprepared. Here's what to have ready:</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Your timeline</strong> — How long have you been trying? Note the date you started.</li>
				<li><strong>Menstrual cycle info</strong> — Average cycle length, regularity, any changes.</li>
				<li><strong>Any relevant medical history</strong> — Previous surgeries, conditions (
					<span data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: a hormonal condition that can affect ovulation" class="ohip-tip">
						PCOS
					</span>, 
					<span data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="A condition where tissue similar to the uterine lining grows outside the uterus" class="ohip-tip">
						endometriosis
					</span>, 
					<span data-bs-toggle="tooltip" title="Thyroid disorders can affect hormone levels and interfere with ovulation" class="ohip-tip">
						thyroid
					</span>
				), medications.</li>
				<li><strong>Your clinic preference</strong> — You can ask your family doctor if they recommend a specific fertility clinic, or research on your own using the clinic list above. Consider which clinics are closest to your home or workplace, since you'll need frequent visits. You can also check Google Maps reviews from other patients. For government-funded treatment waitlist times, you'll need to call each clinic directly — most clinics don't publish this information online.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="initial-specialist-box">
			<h5>What Happens After the Referral</h5>
			<p>
				Once you and your family doctor have decided on a clinic, the referral will be sent. From here, you'll 
				wait for the clinic to contact you. This is usually a phone call from the clinic's intake team. They may 
				ask which fertility specialist you'd like to see at their clinic. If you don't have a preference, they 
				will assign one for you.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-2">
				The clinic will also ask for your email address and send you intake forms, consent documents, and other 
				paperwork to complete online before your first visit.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-2">
				Your first appointment with the fertility specialist can be in-person or virtual, depending on the clinic. 
				Both you and your partner are usually expected to attend. Expect the consultation to last about 30 to 45 minutes.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-2">
				Some clinics will send forms ahead of time so you can fill in your medical history and basic information 
				before the visit, which helps the clinic set up your file. Keep in mind that some specialists may not go 
				into detail about the investigative process during this first meeting. Between answering your questions 
				and covering other topics, the time can go by quickly.
			</p>
		</div>

		<%- include('partials/quiz-stage1') %>

		<div class="text-center mt-5">
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/stage2" class="btn btn-outline-sage">Next: The Investigative Cycle →</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

</main>
<%- include('partials/footer.ejs') %>
